# Jidoka: Your First Agent

## Section

This notebook teaches the smallest useful Jidoka loop: define an agent, give a
conversation a session, run one turn, and inspect what happened.

You will learn:

* an agent is the compiled behavior
* a session is the conversation address and context carrier
* `Jidoka.chat/3` is the single turn primitive

## Setup

This notebook installs Jidoka from GitHub until the package ships on Hex. The
`:fast` model alias is configured here the same way you would configure it in
`config/config.exs` in an application.

```elixir
jidoka_dep = {:jidoka, github: "agentjido/jidoka", branch: "main"}

# After Jidoka ships on Hex:
# jidoka_dep = {:jidoka, "~> 1.0"}

Mix.install(
  [jidoka_dep],
  config: [
    jidoka: [
      model_aliases: %{
        fast: "anthropic:claude-haiku-4-5"
      }
    ]
  ],
  consolidate_protocols: false
)

live_provider? =
  "ANTHROPIC_API_KEY"
  |> System.get_env("")
  |> String.trim()
  |> then(&(String.starts_with?(&1, "sk-ant-") and byte_size(&1) > 20))

%{
  jidoka_source: :github,
  fast_model: "anthropic:claude-haiku-4-5",
  live_provider: if(live_provider?, do: :ready, else: :missing_anthropic_api_key)
}
```

## Define An Agent

An agent has a stable id, a model, and instructions. That is enough to compile a
runtime module and run turns.

```elixir
defmodule Demo.Assistant do
  use Jidoka.Agent

  agent :first_agent_assistant do
    model :fast
    instructions "Answer clearly and concisely."
  end
end

%{
  id: Demo.Assistant.id(),
  model: Demo.Assistant.configured_model(),
  instructions: Demo.Assistant.instructions(),
  runtime_module: Demo.Assistant.runtime_module()
}
```

## Give The Conversation A Session

A session is data, not a process. It names the conversation, carries runtime
context, and tells Jidoka which runtime agent should handle the turn.

```elixir
session =
  Demo.Assistant
  |> Jidoka.session("user-123", context: %{actor_id: "user_123", tenant: "demo"})

%{
  session_id: session.id,
  agent_id: session.agent_id,
  conversation_id: session.conversation_id,
  context: session.context,
  chat_opts: Jidoka.Session.chat_opts(session)
}
```

## Inspect The Compiled Surface

Inspection is useful before a model ever runs. It shows the public agent shape
that Jidoka generated from the DSL.

```elixir
{:ok, inspection} = Jidoka.inspect_agent(Demo.Assistant)

%{
  id: inspection.id,
  tools: inspection.tools,
  controls: Demo.Assistant.controls(),
  result: inspection.result,
  schedules: Demo.Assistant.schedules()
}
```

## Run A Provider-Free Turn

For a deterministic teaching run, use an input control that interrupts before the
provider call. This proves the normal chat path starts the runtime agent, merges
session context, creates a request, and records trace data without requiring an
API key.

```elixir
stop_before_provider = fn input ->
  Jidoka.Approval.request("Stop before provider execution.",
    data: %{
      request_id: input.request_id,
      context: Jidoka.Context.strip_internal(input.context)
    }
  )
end

{:interrupt, interrupt} =
  Jidoka.chat(session, "Summarize this ticket.", controls: [input: stop_before_provider])

%{
  kind: interrupt.kind,
  message: interrupt.message,
  request_id: interrupt.data.request_id,
  context_seen_by_control: interrupt.data.context
}
```

## Debug The Turn

The same session can address inspection, trace, and AgentView helpers. This is
the core debugging loop: run a turn, inspect the request, inspect the trace, then
project the conversation state.

```elixir
{:ok, request} = Jidoka.inspect_request(session)
{:ok, trace} = Jidoka.inspect_trace(session)
{:ok, view} = Jidoka.Session.snapshot(session)

%{
  request: %{
    id: request.request_id,
    status: request.status,
    input_message: request.input_message
  },
  trace_events: Enum.map(trace.events, &{&1.category, &1.event}),
  view: %{
    kind: view.kind,
    agent_id: view.agent_id,
    context_ref: view.context_ref,
    message_count: length(view.visible_messages)
  }
}
```

## Optional Live Turn

This cell runs only when the setup cell detects a usable `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.
The provider-free cells above are still the default teaching path.

```elixir
if live_provider? do
  live_session =
    Demo.Assistant
    |> Jidoka.session("live-user-123", context: %{actor_id: "user_123", tenant: "demo"})

  Jidoka.chat(live_session, "In one sentence, explain what a Jidoka session is.")
else
  {:skipped, "Set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY to run the optional live provider cell."}
end
```

## What Changed

Jidoka owned the agent DSL, the session address, the chat turn, and the debugging
projection. Your application still owns the real user id, tenant id, provider
credentials, supervision decisions, and durable storage policy.
